# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: container-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:container-security/container-virtualization] In software engineering, **containerization** is operating-system-level virtualization or application-level virtualization over multiple resources so that software applications can run in isolated user spaces called *containers* in any cloud or non-cloud environment, regardless of type or vendor.
[src:container-security/container-virtualization] The term "container" has different meanings in different contexts, and it is important to ensure that the intended definition aligns with the audience's understanding.
[src:container-security/container-virtualization] Each *container* is basically a fully functional and portable cloud or non-cloud computing environment surrounding the application and keeping it independent of other environments running in parallel.
[src:container-security/container-virtualization] Individually, each container simulates a different software application and runs isolated processes by bundling related configuration files, libraries and dependencies.
[src:container-security/container-virtualization] But, collectively, multiple containers share a common operating system kernel (OS).
[src:container-security/container-virtualization] In recent times, containerization technology has been widely adopted by cloud computing platforms like Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, and IBM Cloud.
[src:container-security/container-virtualization] Containerization has also been pursued by the U.S.
[src:container-security/container-virtualization] Department of Defense as a way of more rapidly developing and fielding software updates, with first application in its F-22 air superiority fighter.
[src:container-security/container-virtualization] Container orchestration or container management is mostly used in the context of application containers.
[src:container-security/container-virtualization] Implementations providing such orchestration include Kubernetes and Docker swarm.
[src:container-security/container-virtualization] This includes functionality to create a cluster, to upgrade the software or repair it, balance the load between existing instances, scale by starting or stopping instances to adapt to the number of users, to log activities and monitor produced logs or the application itself by querying sensors.
[src:container-security/container-virtualization] Open-source implementations of such software include OKD and Rancher.
[src:container-security/container-virtualization] Quite a number of companies provide container cluster management as a managed service, like Alibaba, Amazon, Google, and Microsoft.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Docker is the most popular containerization technology.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] When used correctly, it can enhance security compared to running applications directly on the host system.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] However, certain misconfigurations can reduce security levels or introduce new vulnerabilities.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] The aim of this cheat sheet is to provide a straightforward list of common security errors and best practices to assist in securing your Docker containers.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] To protect against known container escape vulnerabilities like Leaky Vessels, which typically result in the attacker gaining root access to the host, it's vital to keep both the host and Docker up to date.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] This includes regularly updating the host kernel as well as the Docker Engine.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] This is due to the fact that containers share the host's kernel.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] If the host's kernel is vulnerable, the containers are also vulnerable.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] For example, the kernel privilege escalation exploit, Dirty COW, executed inside a well-insulated container would still result in root access on a vulnerable host.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Docker socket */var/run/docker.sock* is the UNIX socket that Docker is listening to.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] This is the primary entry point for the Docker API.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Giving someone access to it is equivalent to giving unrestricted root access to your host.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Configuring the container to use an unprivileged user is the best way to prevent privilege escalation attacks.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] More information about this topic can be found at Docker official documentation.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] For additional security, you can also run in rootless mode, which is discussed in Rule #11.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] As a Kubernetes cluster administrator, you can configure a hardened default using the `Restricted` level with built-in Pod Security admission controller, if greater customization is desired consider using Admission Webhooks or a third party alternative.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Linux kernel capabilities are a set of privileges that can be used by privileged.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Docker, by default, runs with only a subset of capabilities.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] You can change it and drop some capabilities (using `--cap-drop`) to harden your docker containers, or add some capabilities (using `--cap-add`) if needed.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Remember not to run containers with the `--privileged` flag - this will add ALL Linux kernel capabilities to the container.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] The most secure setup is to drop all capabilities `--cap-drop all` and then add only required ones.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Always run your docker images with `--security-opt=no-new-privileges` in order to prevent privilege escalation.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] This will prevent the container from gaining new privileges via `setuid` or `setgid` binaries.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Inter-Container Connectivity (icc) is enabled by default, allowing all containers to communicate with each other through the `docker0` bridged network.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Instead of using the `--icc=false` flag with the Docker daemon, which completely disables inter-container communication, consider defining specific network configurations.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] This can be achieved by creating custom Docker networks and specifying which containers should be attached to them.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] This method provides more granular control over container communication.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] For detailed guidance on configuring Docker networks for container communication, refer to the Docker Documentation.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] In Kubernetes environments, Network Policies can be used to define rules that regulate pod interactions within the cluster.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] These policies provide a robust framework to control how pods communicate with each other and with other network endpoints.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Additionally, Network Policy Editor simplifies the creation and management of network policies, making it more accessible to define complex networking rules through a user-friendly interface.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] UFW (Uncomplicated Firewall) is a popular host-based firewall for Linux.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] A common misconception is that firewall rules protect all inbound traffic — including traffic destined for Docker containers.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] However, **Docker manages its own `iptables` and `nftables` rules directly and bypasses UFW entirely**.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Note that other tools that use `iptables` or `nftables` can also have conflicts similar to UFW.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] If you are using other firewall tools, you should check if they are working correctly.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] When you publish a port with `-p 8000:8000`, Docker inserts `iptables` rules that open that port to **all interfaces and all source addresses**, and these rules are typically accepted before explicit firewall `DENY` rules are applied.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] As a result, traffic may be allowed through regardless of any `DENY` rules you have set, which can unintentionally expose container services to the public internet.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Refer to the Docker and iptables documentation for a deeper explanation of how Docker interacts with the host firewall.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] The best way to avoid DoS attacks is by limiting resources.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] You can limit memory, CPU, maximum number of restarts (`--restart=on-failure:<number_of_restarts>`), maximum number of file descriptors (`--ulimit nofile=<number>`) and maximum number of processes (`--ulimit nproc=<number>`).
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] CI/CD pipelines are a crucial part of the software development lifecycle and should include various security checks such as lint checks, static code analysis, and container scanning.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Many issues can be prevented by following some best practices when writing the Dockerfile.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] However, adding a security linter as a step in the build pipeline can go a long way in avoiding further headaches.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Container scanning tools are especially important as part of a successful security strategy.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] They can detect known vulnerabilities, secrets and misconfigurations in container images and provide a report of the findings with recommendations on how to fix them.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] By default, the Docker daemon is configured to have a base logging level of `info`.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] This can be verified by checking the daemon configuration file `/etc/docker/daemon.json` for the`log-level` key.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] If the key is not present, the default logging level is `info`.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Additionally, if the docker daemon is started with the `--log-level` option, the value of the `log-level` key in the configuration file will be overridden.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Setting an appropriate log level, configures the Docker daemon to log events that you would want to review later.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] A base log level of 'info' and above would capture all logs except the debug logs.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Until and unless required, you should not run docker daemon at the 'debug' log level.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Rootless mode ensures that the Docker daemon and containers are running as an unprivileged user, which means that even if an attacker breaks out of the container, they will not have root privileges on the host, which in turn substantially limits the attack surface.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] This is different to userns-remap mode, where the daemon still operates with root privileges.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Evaluate the specific requirements and security posture of your environment to determine if rootless mode is the best choice for you.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] For environments where security is a paramount concern and the limitations of rootless mode do not interfere with operational requirements, it is a strongly recommended configuration.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Alternatively consider using Podman as an alternative to Docker.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Read more about rootless mode and its limitations, installation and usage instructions on Docker documentation page.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Docker Secrets provide a secure way to store and manage sensitive data such as passwords, tokens, and SSH keys.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Using Docker Secrets helps in avoiding the exposure of sensitive data in container images or in runtime commands.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] While Docker Secrets generally provide a secure way to manage sensitive data in Docker environments, this approach is not recommended for Kubernetes, where secrets are stored in plaintext by default.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] In Kubernetes, consider using additional security measures such as etcd encryption, or third-party tools.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Refer to the Secrets Management Cheat Sheet for more information.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Building on the principles in Rule #9, enhancing supply chain security involves implementing additional measures to secure the entire lifecycle of container images from creation to deployment.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Podman is an OCI-compliant, open-source container management tool developed by Red Hat that provides a Docker-compatible command-line interface and a desktop application for managing containers.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] It is designed to be a more secure and lightweight alternative to Docker, especially for environments where secure defaults are preferred.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] Rootless Containers: The fork-exec model facilitates Podman's ability to run containers without requiring root privileges.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] When a non-root user initiates a container start, Podman forks and execs under the user's permissions.
[src:container-security/docker-security-cheat-sheet] SELinux Integration: Podman is built to work with SELinux, which provides an additional layer of security by enforcing mandatory access controls on containers and their interactions with the host system.
[src:container-security/docker-software] The core software that runs and manages these containers is called **Docker Engine**.
[src:container-security/docker-software] Docker was first released in 2013 and continues to be developed by Docker, Inc.
[src:container-security/docker-software] The platform includes both free and paid tiers.
[src:container-security/docker-software] Solomon Hykes started the Docker project in France as an internal project within dotCloud, a platform-as-a-service company.
[src:container-security/docker-software] dotCloud Inc. was founded by Kamel Founadi, Hykes, and Sebastien Pahl during the Y Combinator Summer 2010 startup incubator group and launched in 2011, and renamed to Docker Inc in 2013.
[src:container-security/docker-software] Docker debuted to the public in Santa Clara at PyCon in 2013.
[src:container-security/docker-software] It was released as open-source in March 2013.
[src:container-security/docker-software] At the time, it used LXC as its default execution environment.
[src:container-security/docker-software] One year later, with the release of version 0.9, Docker replaced LXC with its own component, *libcontainer*, which was written in the Go programming language.
[src:container-security/docker-software] In 2017, Docker created the Moby project for open research and development.
[src:container-security/docker-software] In March 2026, the Communications of the ACM featured Docker as the cover article in a retrospective article of the past decade.
[src:container-security/docker-software] Containers are isolated from one another and bundle their own software, libraries and configuration files; they can communicate with each other through well-defined channels.
[src:container-security/docker-software] Because all of the containers share the services of a single operating system kernel, they use fewer resources than virtual machines.
[src:container-security/docker-software] Docker can package an application and its dependencies in a virtual container that can, in principle, run on any Linux, Windows, or macOS computer.
[src:container-security/docker-software] This enables the application to run in a variety of locations, such as on-premises, in public *(see decentralized computing, distributed computing, and cloud computing)* or private cloud.
[src:container-security/docker-software] Docker on macOS uses a Linux virtual machine to run the containers.
[src:container-security/docker-software] Because Docker containers are lightweight, a single server or virtual machine can run several containers simultaneously.
[src:container-security/docker-software] A 2018 analysis found that a typical Docker use case involves running eight containers per host, and that a quarter of analyzed organizations run 18 or more per host.
[src:container-security/docker-software] It can also be installed on a single board computer like the Raspberry Pi.
[src:container-security/docker-software] The Linux kernel's support for namespaces mostly isolates an application's view of the operating environment, including process trees, network, user IDs and mounted file systems, while the kernel's cgroups provide resource limiting for memory and CPU.
[src:container-security/docker-software] Since version 0.9, Docker includes its own component (called libcontainer) to use virtualization facilities provided directly by the Linux kernel, in addition to using abstracted virtualization interfaces via libvirt, LXC and systemd-nspawn.
[src:container-security/docker-software] Docker implements a high-level API to provide lightweight containers that run processes in isolation.
[src:container-security/docker-software] , is a persistent process that manages Docker containers and handles container objects.
[src:container-security/docker-software] The daemon listens for requests that are sent via the Docker Engine API.
[src:container-security/docker-software] (CLI) that allows users to interact with Docker daemons.
[src:container-security/docker-software] Docker objects are various entities used to assemble an application in Docker.
[src:container-security/docker-software] The main classes of Docker objects are images, containers, and services.
[src:container-security/docker-software] A Docker registry is a repository for Docker images.
[src:container-security/docker-software] Docker clients connect to registries to download ("pull") images for use or upload ("push") images that they have built.
[src:container-security/docker-software] Docker Hub is the default registry where Docker looks for images.
[src:container-security/docker-software] Docker registries also allow the creation of notifications based on events.
[src:container-security/docker-software] A Dockerfile is a text file that commonly specifies several aspects of a Docker container: the Linux distribution, installation commands for the programming language runtime environment and application source code.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] A **hypervisor**, also known as a **virtual machine monitor** (**VMM**), is a type of computer software, firmware or hardware that creates and runs virtual machines.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] A computer on which a hypervisor runs one or more virtual machines is called a *host machine* or *virtualization server*, and each virtual machine is called a *guest machine*.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] The hypervisor presents the guest operating systems with a virtual operating platform and manages the execution of the guest operating systems.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Unlike an emulator, the guest executes most instructions on the native hardware.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Multiple instances of a variety of operating systems may share the virtualized hardware resources: for example, Linux, Windows, and macOS instances can all run on a single physical x86 machine.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] This contrasts with operating system-level virtualization, where all instances (usually called *containers*) must share a single kernel, though the guest operating systems can differ in user space, such as different Linux distributions with the same kernel.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] The term *hypervisor* is a variant of *supervisor*, a traditional term for the kernel of an operating system: the hypervisor is the supervisor of the supervisors, with *hyper-* used as a stronger variant of *super-*.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] The term dates to circa 1970; IBM coined it for software that ran OS/360 and the 7090 emulator concurrently on the 360/65 and later used it for the DIAG handler of CP-67.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] In the earlier CP/CMS (1967) system, the term *Control Program* was used instead.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Some literature, especially in microkernel contexts, makes a distinction between *hypervisor* and *virtual machine monitor* (*VMM*).
[src:container-security/hypervisor] There, both components form the overall *virtualization stack* of a certain system.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] *Hypervisor* refers to kernel-space functionality and VMM to user-space functionality.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Specifically in these contexts, a *hypervisor* is a microkernel implementing virtualization infrastructure that must run in kernel-space for technical reasons, such as Intel VMX.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Microkernels implementing virtualization mechanisms are also referred to as *microhypervisor*.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Applying this terminology to Linux, KVM is a *hypervisor* and QEMU or Cloud Hypervisor are VMMs utilizing KVM as hypervisor.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] In his 1973 thesis *Architectural Principles for Virtual Computer Systems*, Robert P.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] These hypervisors run directly on the host's hardware to control the hardware and to manage guest operating systems.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] The first hypervisors, which IBM developed in the 1960s, were native hypervisors.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] These hypervisors run on a conventional operating system (OS) just as other computer programs do.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Type-2 hypervisors abstract guest operating systems from the host operating system, effectively creating an isolated system that can be interacted with by the host.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] The distinction between these two types is not always clear.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] For instance, KVM and bhyve are kernel modules that effectively convert the host operating system to a type-1 hypervisor.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] The first hypervisors providing full virtualization were the test tool SIMMON and the one-off IBM CP-40 research system, which began production use in January 1967 and became the first version of the IBM CP/CMS operating system.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] CP-40 ran on a S/360-40 modified at the Cambridge Scientific Center to support dynamic address translation, a feature that enabled virtualization.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Prior to this time, computer hardware had only been virtualized to the extent to allow multiple user applications to run concurrently, such as in CTSS and IBM M44/44X.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] With CP-40, the hardware's *supervisor state* was virtualized as well, allowing multiple operating systems to run concurrently in separate virtual machine contexts.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Programmers soon implemented CP-40 (as CP-67) for the IBM System/360-67, the first production computer system capable of full virtualization.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] IBM shipped this machine in 1966; it included page-translation-table hardware for virtual memory and other techniques that allowed a full virtualization of all kernel tasks, including I/O and interrupt handling.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] (The "official" operating system, the ill-fated TSS/360, did not employ full virtualization.) Both CP-40 and CP-67 began production use in 1967.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] CP/CMS was available to IBM customers from 1968 to early 1970s, in source code form without support.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] CP/CMS formed part of IBM's attempt to build robust time-sharing systems for its mainframe computers.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] By running multiple operating systems concurrently, the hypervisor increased system robustness and stability: Even if one operating system crashed, the others would continue working without interruption.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Indeed, this even allowed beta or experimental versions of operating systems‍—‌or even of new hardware‍—‌to be deployed and debugged, without jeopardizing the stable main production system, and without requiring costly additional development systems.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] IBM announced its System/370 series in 1970 without the virtual memory feature needed for virtualization, but added it in the August 1972 Advanced Function announcement.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Virtualization has been featured in all successor systems, such that all modern-day IBM mainframes, including the zSeries line, retain backward compatibility with the 1960s-era IBM S/360 line.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] The 1972 announcement also included VM/370, a reimplementation of CP/CMS for the S/370.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Unlike CP/CMS, IBM provided support for this version (though it was still distributed in source code form for several releases).
[src:container-security/hypervisor] *VM* stands for *Virtual Machine*, emphasizing that all, not just some, of the hardware interfaces are virtualized.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Both VM and CP/CMS enjoyed early acceptance and rapid development by universities, corporate users, and time-sharing vendors, as well as within IBM.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Users played an active role in ongoing development, anticipating trends seen in modern open source projects.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] However, in a series of disputed and bitter battles, time-sharing lost out to batch processing through IBM political infighting, and VM remained IBM's "other" mainframe operating system for decades, losing to MVS.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] It enjoyed a resurgence of popularity and support from 2000 as the z/VM product, for example as the platform for Linux on IBM Z.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] As mentioned above, the VM control program includes a *hypervisor-call* handler that intercepts DIAG ("Diagnose", opcode x'83') instructions used within a virtual machine.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] This provides fast-path non-virtualized execution of file-system access and other operations (DIAG is a model-dependent privileged instruction, not used in normal programming, and thus is not virtualized.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] It is therefore available for use as a signal to the "host" operating system).
[src:container-security/hypervisor] When first implemented in CP/CMS release 3.1, this use of DIAG provided an operating system interface that was analogous to the System/360 Supervisor Call instruction (SVC), but that did not require altering or extending the system's virtualization of SVC.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] In 1985 IBM introduced the PR/SM hypervisor to manage logical partitions (LPAR).
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Major Unix vendors, including HP, IBM, SGI, and Sun Microsystems, have been selling virtualized hardware since before 2000.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] These have generally been large, expensive systems (in the multimillion-dollar range at the high end), although virtualization has also been available on some low- and mid-range systems, such as IBM pSeries servers, HP Superdome series machines, and Sun/Oracle SPARC T series CoolThreads servers.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] IBM provides virtualization partition technology known as logical partitioning (LPAR) on System/390, zSeries, pSeries and IBM AS/400 systems.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] For IBM's Power Systems, the POWER Hypervisor (PHYP) is a native (bare-metal) hypervisor in firmware and provides isolation between LPARs.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Processor capacity is provided to LPARs in either a dedicated fashion or on an entitlement basis where unused capacity is harvested and can be re-allocated to busy workloads.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Groups of LPARs can have their processor capacity managed as if they were in a "pool" - IBM refers to this capability as Multiple Shared-Processor Pools (MSPPs) and implements it in servers with the POWER6 processor.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] LPAR and MSPP capacity allocations can be dynamically changed.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Memory is allocated to each LPAR (at LPAR initiation or dynamically) and is address-controlled by the POWER Hypervisor.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] For real-mode addressing by operating systems (AIX, Linux, IBM i), the Power processors (POWER4 onwards) have designed virtualization capabilities where a hardware address-offset is evaluated with the OS address-offset to arrive at the physical memory address.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Input/Output (I/O) adapters can be exclusively "owned" by LPARs or shared by LPARs through an appliance partition known as the Virtual I/O Server (VIOS).
[src:container-security/hypervisor] HPE provides HP Integrity Virtual Machines (Integrity VM) to host multiple operating systems on their Itanium powered Integrity systems.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Itanium can run HP-UX, Linux, Windows and OpenVMS, and these environments are also supported as virtual servers on HP's Integrity VM platform.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] While it heavily leverages HP-UX, the Integrity VM hypervisor is really a hybrid that runs on bare-metal while guests are executing.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Running normal HP-UX applications on an Integrity VM host is heavily discouraged, because Integrity VM implements its own memory management, scheduling and I/O policies that are tuned for virtual machines and are not as effective for normal applications.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] HPE also provides more rigid partitioning of their Integrity and HP9000 systems by way of VPAR and nPar technology, the former offering shared resource partitioning and the latter offering complete I/O and processing isolation.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] The flexibility of virtual server environment (VSE) has given way to its use more frequently in newer deployments.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Wind River "Carrier Grade Linux" also runs on Sun's Hypervisor.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Full virtualization on SPARC processors proved straightforward: since its inception in the mid-1980s Sun deliberately kept the SPARC architecture clean of artifacts that would have impeded virtualization.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Similar trends have occurred with x86/x86-64 server platforms, where open-source projects such as Xen have led virtualization efforts.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] These include hypervisors built on Linux and Solaris kernels as well as custom kernels.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Since these technologies span from large systems down to desktops, they are described in the next section.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] x86 virtualization was introduced in the 1990s, with its emulation being included in Bochs.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Intel and AMD released their first x86 processors with hardware virtualisation in 2005 with Intel VT-x (code-named Vanderpool) and AMD-V (code-named Pacifica).
[src:container-security/hypervisor] An alternative approach requires modifying the guest operating system to make a system call to the underlying hypervisor, rather than executing machine I/O instructions that the hypervisor simulates.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] This is called paravirtualization in Xen, a "hypercall" in Parallels Workstation, and a "DIAGNOSE code" in IBM VM.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Some microkernels, such as Mach and L4, are flexible enough to allow paravirtualization of guest operating systems.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Embedded hypervisors, targeting embedded systems and certain real-time operating system (RTOS) environments, are designed with different requirements when compared to desktop and enterprise systems, including robustness, security and real-time capabilities.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] The resource-constrained nature of multiple embedded systems, especially battery-powered mobile systems, imposes a further requirement for small memory-size and low overhead.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Finally, in contrast to the ubiquity of the x86 architecture in the PC world, the embedded world uses a wider variety of architectures and less standardized environments.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Support for virtualization requires memory protection (in the form of a memory management unit or at least a memory protection unit) and a distinction between user mode and privileged mode, which rules out most microcontrollers.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] This still leaves x86, MIPS, ARM and PowerPC as widely deployed architectures on medium- to high-end embedded systems.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] As manufacturers of embedded systems usually have the source code to their operating systems, they have less need for full virtualization in this space.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Instead, the performance advantages of paravirtualization make this usually the virtualization technology of choice.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Nevertheless, ARM and MIPS have recently added full virtualization support as an IP option and has included it in their latest high-end processors and architecture versions, such as ARM Cortex-A15 MPCore and ARMv8 EL2.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] Implementation of the concept has allegedly occurred in the SubVirt laboratory rootkit (developed jointly by Microsoft and University of Michigan researchers) as well as in the Blue Pill malware package.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] However, such assertions have been disputed by others who claim that it would be possible to detect the presence of a hypervisor-based rootkit.
[src:container-security/hypervisor] In 2009, researchers from Microsoft and North Carolina State University demonstrated a hypervisor-layer anti-rootkit called Hooksafe that can provide generic protection against kernel-mode rootkits.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] This cheat sheet provides a starting point for securing a Kubernetes cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] For more information about Kubernetes, refer to the Appendix.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Join the kubernetes-announce group (https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/issues-security/security/) for emails about security announcements.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] See the security reporting page (https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/issues-security/security) for more on how to report vulnerabilities.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Kubernetes is an open source container orchestration engine for automating deployment, scaling, and management of containerized applications.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] The open source project is hosted by the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF).
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] When you deploy Kubernetes, you get a cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] A Kubernetes cluster consists of a set of worker machines, called nodes that run containerized applications.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] The control plane manages the worker nodes and the Pods in the cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] The control plane's components make global decisions about the cluster, as well as detecting and responding to cluster events.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It consists of components such as kube-apiserver, etcd, kube-scheduler, kube-controller-manager and cloud-controller-manager.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Node components run on every node, maintaining running pods and providing the Kubernetes runtime environment.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It consists of components such as kubelet, kube-proxy and container runtime.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Kubernetes can be deployed in different ways: on bare metal, on-premise, and in the public cloud (a custom Kubernetes build on virtual machines OR use a managed service).
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Since Kubernetes is designed to be highly portable, customers can easily and migrate their workloads and switch between multiple installations.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Because Kubernetes can be designed to fit a large variety of scenarios, this flexibility is a weakness when it comes to securing Kubernetes clusters.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] The engineers responsible for deploying the Kubernetes platform must know about all the potential attack vectors and vulnerabilities for their clusters.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Since no one can track all potential attack vectors for your Kubernetes cluster, the first and best defense is to always run the latest stable version of Kubernetes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] In case vulnerabilities are found in running containers, it is recommended to always update the source image and redeploy the containers.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] The Kubernetes project maintains release branches for the most recent three minor releases and it backports the applicable fixes, including security fixes, to those three release branches, depending on severity and feasibility.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Patch releases are cut from those branches at a regular cadence, plus additional urgent releases, when required.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Hence it is always recommended to upgrade the Kubernetes cluster to the latest available stable version.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It is recommended to refer to the version skew policy for further details https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/release/version-skew-policy/.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] There are several techniques such as rolling updates, and node pool migrations that allow you to complete an update with minimal disruption and downtime.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] This section discusses how to secure Kubernetes components.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] The Kubernetes dashboard is a webapp for managing your cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It is not a part of the Kubernetes cluster itself, it has to be installed by the owners of the cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Thus, there are a lot of tutorials on how to do this.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Unfortunately, most of them create a service account with very high privileges.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] This caused Tesla and some others to be hacked via such a poorly configured K8s dashboard.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] etcd is a critical Kubernetes component which stores information on states and secrets, and it should be protected differently from the rest of your cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Write access to the API server's etcd is equivalent to gaining root on the entire cluster, and even read access can be used to escalate privileges fairly easily.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] The Kubernetes scheduler will search etcd for pod definitions that do not have a node.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It then sends the pods it finds to an available kubelet for scheduling.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Validation for submitted pods is performed by the API server before it writes them to etcd, so malicious users writing directly to etcd can bypass many security mechanisms - e.g.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Administrators should always use strong credentials from the API servers to their etcd server, such as mutual auth via TLS client certificates, and it is often recommended to isolate the etcd servers behind a firewall that only the API servers may access.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Allowing other components within the cluster to access the primary etcd instance with read or write access to the full keyspace is equivalent to granting cluster-admin access.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Using separate etcd instances for other components or using etcd ACLs to restrict read and write access to a subset of the keyspace is strongly recommended.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It is highly recommended to configure authentication and authorization on the cluster and cluster nodes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Since Kubernetes clusters usually listen on a range of well-defined and distinctive ports, it is easier for attackers to identify the clusters and attack them.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] An overview of the default ports used in Kubernetes is provided below.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Make sure that your network blocks access to ports, and you should seriously consider limiting access to the Kubernetes API server to trusted networks.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] The first line of defense of Kubernetes against attackers is limiting and securing access to API requests, because those requests are used to control the Kubernetes platform.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] For more information, refer to the documentation at https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/access-authn-authz/controlling-access/.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] In Kubernetes, you must be authenticated (logged in) before your request can be authorized (granted permission to access), and Kubernetes expects attributes that are common to REST API requests.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] This means that existing organization-wide or cloud-provider-wide access control systems which may handle other APIs work with Kubernetes authorization.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] When Kubernetes authorizes API requests using the API server, permissions are denied by default.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It evaluates all of the request attributes against all policies and allows or denies the request.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] All parts of an API request must be allowed by some policy in order to proceed.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Due to the weakness of Kubernetes' internal mechanisms for authenticating APIs, we strongly recommended that larger or production clusters use one of the external API authentication methods.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] In addition to choosing the appropriate authentication system, API access should be considered privileged and use Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) for all user access.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] For more information, consult Kubernetes authentication reference documentation at https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/access-authn-authz/authentication.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Kubernetes provides a number of internal mechanisms for API server authentication but these are usually only suitable for non-production or small clusters.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] We will briefly discuss each internal mechanism and explain why you should not use them.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Role-based access control (RBAC) is a method for regulating access to computer or network resources based on the roles of individual users within your organization.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Fortunately, Kubernetes comes with an integrated Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) component with default roles that allow you to define user responsibilities depending on what actions a client might want to perform.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] You should use the Node and RBAC authorizers together in combination with the NodeRestriction admission plugin.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] The RBAC component matches an incoming user or group to a set of permissions linked to roles.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] These permissions combine verbs (get, create, delete) with resources (pods, services, nodes) and can be namespace or cluster scoped.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] RBAC authorization uses the rbac.authorization.k8s.io API group to drive authorization decisions, allowing you to dynamically configure policies through the Kubernetes API.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Kubelets expose HTTPS endpoints which grant powerful control over the node and containers.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] By default Kubelets allow unauthenticated access to this API.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Production clusters should enable Kubelet authentication and authorization.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] During the build phase, you should secure your Kubernetes container images by building secure images and scanning those images for any known vulnerabilities.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] A container image (CI) is an immutable, lightweight, standalone package that contains everything required to run an application — the application code, runtime, system libraries, configuration and system tools.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Images are built as layered, read-only artifacts that are portable between hosts but share the host machine’s operating system kernel.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] (https://www.docker.com/resources/what-container).
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Your CIs must be built on a approved and secure base image.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] This base image must be scanned and monitored at regular intervals to ensure that all CIs are based on a secure and authentic image.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Implement strong governance policies that determine how images are built and stored in trusted image registries.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Ensure your images (and any third-party tools you include) are up-to-date and use the latest versions of their components.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Downloading and running CIs from unknown sources is very dangerous.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Make sure that only images adhering to the organization’s policy are allowed to run, or else the organization is open to risk of running vulnerable or even malicious containers.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] The Kubernetes container registry serves as a central repository of all container images in the system.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Depending on your needs, you can utilize a public repository or have a private repository as the container registry.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] We recommend that you store your approved images in a private registry and only push approved images to these registries, which automatically reduces the number of potential images that enter your pipeline down to a fraction of the hundreds of thousands of publicly available images.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Also, we strongly recommend that you add a CI pipeline that integrates security assessment (like vulnerability scanning) into the build process.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] This pipeline should vet all code that is approved for production and is used to build the images.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] After an image is built, it should be scanned for security vulnerabilities.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Only if no issues are found, then the image would be pushed to a private registry then deployed to production.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] If the security assessment mechanism fails any code, it should create a failure in the pipeline, which will help you find images with security problems and prevent them from entering the image registry.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Many source code repositories provide scanning capabilities (e.g.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Github, GitLab), and many CI tools offer integration with open source vulnerability scanners such as Trivy or Grype.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Projects are developing image authorization plugins for Kubernetes that prevent unauthorized images from shipping.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] For more information, refer to the PR https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/pull/27129.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] As a best practice, Google and other tech giants have strictly limiting the code in their runtime container for years.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] This approach improves the signal-to-noise of scanners (e.g.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] CVE) and reduces the burden of establishing provenance to just what you need.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Consider using minimal CIs such as distroless images (see below).
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] If this is not possible, do not include OS package managers or shells in CIs because they may have unknown vulnerabilities.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] If you absolutely must include any OS packages, remove the package manager at a later step in the generation process.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Distroless images sharply reduce the attack surface because they do not include shells and contain fewer packages than other images.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] For more information on distroless images, refer to https://github.com/GoogleContainerTools/distroless.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] An empty image, ideal for statically compiled languages like Go, because the image is empty - the attack surface it is truly minimal - only your code!
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Once a Kubernetes infrastructure is in place, you must configure it securely before any workloads are deployed.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] And as you configure your infrastructure, ensure that you have visibility into what CIs are being deployed and how they are being deployed or else you will not be able to identify and respond to security policy violations.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Namespaces give you the ability to create logical partitions, enforce separation of your resources and limit the scope of user permissions.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] To set the namespace for a current request, use the --namespace flag.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Since new vulnerabilities are always being discovered, you may not always know if your containers may have recently-disclosed vulnerabilities (CVEs) or outdated packages.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] To maintain a strong security posture, do regular production scanning of first-party containers (applications you have built and previously scanned) as well as third-party containers (which are sourced from trusted repository and vendors).
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Open Source projects such as Trivy, Grype, and Clair can assist in identifying and prioritizing vulnerabilities.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] The security context is a property that is defined in the deployment yaml and controls the security parameters for all pod/container/volumes, and it should be applied throughout your infrastructure.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] When the security context property is properly implemented everywhere, it can eliminate entire classes of attacks that rely on privileged access.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] For example, any attack that depends on installing software or writing to the file system will be stopped if you specify read-only root file systems in the security context.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] When you are configuring the security context for your pods, only grant the privileges that are needed for the resources to function in your containers and volumes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] SecurityContext->**Capabilities** Description: Controls the Linux capabilities assigned to the container.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] SecurityContext->**readOnlyRootFilesystem** Description: Controls whether a container will be able to write into the root filesystem.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] We strongly recommend that all your containers should adhere to the principle of least privilege, since your security risk is heavily influenced by the capabilities, role bindings, and privileges given to containers.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Each container should only have the minimum privileges and capabilities that allows it to perform its intended function.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Pod Security Standards combined with the Pod Security Admission Controller allow cluster administrators to enforce requirements on a pods `securityContext` fields.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Each of the profiles have defined settings baselines that can be found in more detail here.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] The Pod Security Admission Controller allows you to enforce, audit, or warn upon the violation of a defined policy.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] `audit` and `warn` modes can be utilized to determine if a particular Pod Security Standard would normally prevent the deployment of a pod when set to `enforce` mode.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Cluster administrators should properly organize and and enforce policy on cluster namespaces, only permitting the privileged policy on namespaces where it is absolutely required, such as for critical cluster services that require access to the underlying host.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Namespaces should be set to the lowest Pod Security Policy that can be enforced and supports their risk level.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] If more granular policy enforcement is required beyond the three profiles (Privileged, Baseline, Restricted), Third party admission controllers like OPA Gatekeeper or Kyverno, or built-in Validating Admission Policy can be utilized.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] For more information on Pod security policies, refer to the documentation at https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/policy/pod-security-policy/.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] A service mesh is an infrastructure layer that can handle communications between services in applications quickly, securely and reliably, which can help reduce the complexity of managing microservices and deployments.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] They provide a uniform way to secure, connect and monitor microservices. and a service mesh is great at resolving operational challenges and issues when running those containers and microservices.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It generates tracing and telemetry metrics, which make it easy to understand your system and quickly root cause any problems.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It provides security features which quickly identify any compromising traffic that enters your cluster and can secure the services inside your network if they are properly implemented.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It can also help you manage security through mTLS, ingress and egress control, and more.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Since securing microservices is hard, there are many tools that address microservices security.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] However, the service mesh is the most elegant solution for addressing encryption of on-the-wire traffic within the network.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It provides defense with mutual TLS (mTLS) encryption of the traffic between your services, and the mesh can automatically encrypt and decrypt requests and responses, which removes that burden from application developers.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] The mesh can also improve performance by prioritizing the reuse of existing, persistent connections, which reduces the need for the computationally expensive creation of new ones.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] With service mesh, you can secure traffic over the wire and also make strong identity-based authentication and authorizations for each microservice.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] We see that a service mesh has a lot of value of enterprise companies, because a mesh allows you to see whether mTLS is enabled and working between each of your services.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Also, you can get immediate alerts if the security status changes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It allows you to monitor and address compromising traffic as it passes through the mesh.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] For example, if Istio integrates with Kubernetes as an ingress controller, it can take care of load balancing for ingress.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] This allows defenders to add a level of security at the perimeter with ingress rules, while egress control allows you to see and manage external services and control how your services interact with traffic.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It can help security and platform teams set the right macro controls to enforce access controls, while allowing developers to make customizations they need to move quickly within these guardrails.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] A service mesh can help defenders implement a strong Role Based Access Control (RBAC) system, which is arguably one of the most critical requirements in large engineering organizations.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] When proxies, sidecars and other components are introduced an already sophisticated environment, it dramatically increases the complexity of development and operations.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] If a mesh like Istio is added on top of an orchestrator such as Kubernetes, operators need to become experts in both technologies.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Because a service mesh is an invasive and intricate technology, it can significantly slow down an architecture.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Since service meshes are invasive, they force developers and operators to adapt to a highly opinionated platform and conform to its rules.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] There are numerous projects which are able to provide centralized policy management for a Kubernetes cluster, including the Open Policy Agent (OPA) project, Kyverno, or the Validating Admission Policy (a built-in feature released to general availability in 1.30).
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] In order to provide an example with some depth, we will focus on OPA in this cheat sheet.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] OPA was started in 2016 to unify policy enforcement across different technologies and systems, and it can be used to enforce policies on a platform like Kubernetes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Currently, OPA is part of CNCF as an incubating project.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It can create a unified method of enforcing security policy in the stack.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] While developers can impose fine-grained control over the cluster with RBAC and Pod security policies, these technologies only apply to the cluster but not outside the cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Since OPA is a general-purpose, domain-agnostic policy enforcement tool that is not based on any other project, the policy queries and decisions do not follow a specific format.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Thus it can be integrated with APIs, the Linux SSH daemon, an object store like Ceph, and you can use any valid JSON data as request attributes as long as it provides the required data.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] OPA allows you to choose what is input and what is output--for example, you can opt to have OPA return a True or False JSON object, a number, a string, or even a complex data object.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] OPA can provide developers with an already-developed authorization technology so the team doesn’t have to develop one from scratch.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] If you already have a homegrown application authorization solution, you may not want to swap in OPA.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] But if you want to improve developer efficiency by moving to a solution that scales with microservices and allows you to decompose monolithic apps, you’re going to need a distributed authorization system and OPA (or one of the related competitors) could be the answer.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Since Kubernetes gives developers tremendous control over the traditional silos of "compute, networking and storage," they can use it to set up their network exactly the way they want and set up storage exactly the way they want.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] But this means that administrators and security teams must make sure that developers don’t shoot themselves (or their neighbors) in the foot.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It can also allow administrators to make sure that policy changes don’t inadvertently do more damage than good.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] OPA integrates directly into the Kubernetes API server and it has complete authority to reject any resource that the admission policy says does not belong in a cluster—-whether it is compute-related, network-related, storage-related, etc.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Moreover, policy can be run out-of-band to monitor results and OPA's policies can be exposed early in the development lifecycle (e.g. the CICD pipeline or even on developer laptops) if developers need feedback early.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] And finally, OPA can regulate use of service mesh architectures.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Often, administrators ensure that compliance regulations are satisfied by building policies into the service mesh even when modification to source code is involved.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Even if you’re not embedding OPA to implement application authorization logic (the top use case discussed above), you can control the APIs microservices by putting authorization policies into the service mesh.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] But if you are motivated by security, you can implement policies in the service mesh to limit lateral movement within a microservice architecture.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It is important to define resource quotas for containers in Kubernetes, since all resources in a Kubernetes cluster are created with unbounded CPU limits and memory requests/limits by default.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] If you run resource-unbound containers, your system will be in risk of Denial of Service (DoS) or “noisy neighbor” scenarios.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Fortunately, OPA can use resource quotas on a namespace, which will limit the number or capacity of resources granted to that namespace and restrict that namespace by defining its CPU capacity, memory, or persistent disk space.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Additionally, the OPA can limit how many pods, services, or volumes exist in each namespace, and it can restrict the maximum or minimum size of some of the resources above.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] The resource quotas provide default limits when none are specified and prevent users from requesting unreasonably high or low values for commonly reserved resources like memory.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Below is an example of defining namespace resource quota in the appropriate yaml.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It limits the number of pods in the namespace to 4, limits their CPU requests between 1 and 2 and memory requests between 1GB to 2GB.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] For more information on configuring resource quotas, refer to the Kubernetes documentation at https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/policy/resource-quotas/.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] If your cluster runs different applications, a compromised application could attack other neighboring applications.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] This scenario might happen because Kubernetes allows every pod to contact every other pod by default.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] If ingress from an external network endpoint is allowed, the pod will be able to send its traffic to an endpoint outside the cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It is strongly recommended that developers implement network segmentation, because it is a key security control that ensures that containers can only communicate with other approved containers and prevents attackers from pursuing lateral movement across containers.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] However, applying network segmentation in the cloud is challenging because of the “dynamic” nature of container network identities (IPs).
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] While users of Google Cloud Platform can benefit from automatic firewall rules, which prevent cross-cluster communication, other users can apply similar implementations by deploying on-premises using network firewalls or SDN solutions.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Also, the Kubernetes Network SIG is working on methods that will greatly improve the pod-to-pod communication policies.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] A new network policy API should address the need to create firewall rules around pods, limiting the network access that a containerized can have.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] For more information on configuring network policies, refer to the Kubernetes documentation at https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/network-policies.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It is important to learn how sensitive data such as credentials and keys are stored and accessed in your infrastructure.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Kubernetes keeps them in a "secret," which is a small object that contains sensitive data, like a password or token.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] It is best for secrets to be mounted into read-only volumes in your containers, rather than exposing them as environment variables.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Also, secrets must be kept separate from an image or pod or anyone with access to the image would have access to the secret as well, even though a pod is not able to access the secrets of another pod.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Complex applications that handle multiple processes and have public access are especially vulnerable in this regard.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Always encrypt your backups using a well reviewed backup and encryption solution and consider using full disk encryption where possible, because the etcd database contains any information accessible via the Kubernetes API.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Access to this database could provide an attacker with significant visibility into the state of your cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Kubernetes supports encryption at rest, a feature introduced in 1.7, and v1 beta since 1.13, which will encrypt Secret resources in etcd and prevent parties with access to your etcd backups from viewing the content of those secrets.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] While this feature is currently beta, it offers an additional level of defense when backups are not encrypted or an attacker gains read access to etcd.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Since an external secrets manager can store and manage your secrets rather than storing them in Kubernetes Secrets, you may want to consider this security alternative.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] A manager provides a number of benefits over using Kubernetes Secrets, including the ability to handle secrets across multiple clusters (or clouds), and the ability to control and rotate secrets centrally.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] For more information on Secrets and their alternatives, refer to the documentation at https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/configuration/secret/.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Also see the Secrets Management cheat sheet for more details and best practices on managing secrets.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] We strongly recommend that you review the secret material present on the container against the principle of 'least privilege' and assess the risk posed by a compromise.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Remember that open-source tools such as Trivy and Gitleaks can scan container filesystems for sensitive resources, such as API tokens, passwords, and keys.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p01] Such resources would be accessible to any user who had access to the unencrypted container filesystem, whether during build, at rest in a registry or backup, or running.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] When the Kubernetes infrastructure enters the runtime phase, containerized applications are exposed to a slew of new security challenges.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] You must gain visibility into your running environment so you can detect and respond to threats as they arise.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] If you proactively secure your containers and Kubernetes deployments at the build and deploy phases, you can greatly reduce the likelihood of security incidents at runtime and the subsequent effort needed to respond to them.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Detecting anomalies by observing container behavior is generally easier in containers than in virtual machines because of the declarative nature of containers and Kubernetes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] These attributes allow easier introspection into what you have deployed and its expected activity.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] The previously recommended Pod Security Policy is deprecated and replaced by Pod Security Admission, a new feature that allows you to enforce security policies on pods in a Kubernetes cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] It is recommended to use the `baseline` level as a minimum security requirement for all pods to ensure a standard level of security across the cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] However, clusters should strive to apply the `restricted` level which follows pod hardening best practices.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] For more information on configuring Pod Security Admission, refer to the documentation at https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/configure-pod-container/enforce-standards-admission-controller/.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] If containers are hardened containers at runtime, security teams have the ability to detect and respond to threats and anomalies while the containers or workloads are in a running state.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Typically, this is carried out by intercepting the low-level system calls and looking for events that may indicate compromise.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Open source tools such as Falco from Sysdig can help operators get up and running with container runtime security by providing defenders with a large number of out-of-the-box detections as well as the ability to create custom rules.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] When container runtimes are permitted to make direct calls to the host kernel, the kernel often interacts with hardware and devices to respond to the request.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Though Cgroups and namespaces give containers a certain amount of isolation, the kernel still presents a large attack surface.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] When defenders have to deal with multi-tenant and highly untrusted clusters, they often add additional layer of sandboxing to ensure that container breakout and kernel exploits are not present.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Because Linux kernel automatically loads kernel modules from disk if needed in certain circumstances, such as when a piece of hardware is attached or a filesystem is mounted, this can be a significant attack surface.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Of particular relevance to Kubernetes, even unprivileged processes can cause certain network-protocol-related kernel modules to be loaded, just by creating a socket of the appropriate type.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] This situation may allow attackers to exploit a security hole in kernel modules that the administrator assumed was not in use.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] To prevent specific modules from being automatically loaded, you can uninstall them from the node, or add rules to block them.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] To block module loading more generically, you can use a Linux Security Module (such as SELinux) to completely deny the module_request permission to containers, preventing the kernel from loading modules for containers under any circumstances.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] (Pods would still be able to use modules that had been loaded manually, or modules that were loaded by the kernel on behalf of some more-privileged process).
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] When containerized applications are replicated for high availability, fault tolerance, or scale reasons, these replicas should behave nearly identically.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] If a replica has significant deviations from the others, defenders would want further investigation.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] If you chose to use a commercial Kubernetes security vendor, they should support a wide array of integrations with external tools.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Containerized applications typically make extensive use of cluster networking, so observing active networking traffic is a good way to understand how applications interact with each other and identify unexpected communication.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] You should observe your active network traffic and compare that traffic to what is allowed based on your Kubernetes network policies.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] At the same time, comparing the active traffic with what’s allowed gives you valuable information about what isn’t happening but is allowed.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] With that information, you can further tighten your allowed network policies so that it removes superfluous connections and decreases your overall attack surface.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Open source projects like https://github.com/kinvolk/inspektor-gadget or https://github.com/deepfence/PacketStreamer may help with this, and commercial security solutions provide varying degrees of container network traffic analysis.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Contain a successful breach by using Kubernetes native controls to scale suspicious pods to zero or kill then restart instances of breached applications.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] The shorter the lifetime of a secret or credential, the harder it is for an attacker to make use of that credential.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Set short lifetimes on certificates and automate their rotation.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Use an authentication provider that can control how long issued tokens are available and use short lifetimes where possible.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] If you use service account tokens in external integrations, plan to rotate those tokens frequently.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] For example, once the bootstrap phase is complete, a bootstrap token used for setting up nodes should be revoked or its authorization removed.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Kubernetes supplies cluster-based logging, which allows you to log container activity into a central log hub.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] When a cluster is created, the standard output and standard error output of each container can be ingested using a Fluentd agent running on each node (into either Google Stackdriver Logging or into Elasticsearch) and viewed with Kibana.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] The audit logger is a beta feature that records actions taken by the API for later analysis in the event of a compromise.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Ensure logs that are monitoring for anomalous or unwanted API calls, especially any authorization failures (these log entries will have a status message “Forbidden”).
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Authorization failures could mean that an attacker is trying to abuse stolen credentials.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Managed Kubernetes providers, including GKE, provide access to this data in their cloud console and may allow you to set up alerts on authorization failures.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Audit logs can be useful for compliance as they should help you answer the questions of what happened, who did what and when.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Kubernetes provides flexible auditing of kube-apiserver requests based on policies.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] These help you track all activities in chronological order.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Audit policy sets rules which define what events should be recorded and what data is stored when an event includes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] The audit policy object structure is defined in the audit.k8s.io API group.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] When an event is processed, it is compared against the list of rules in order.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] The first matching rule sets the "audit level" of the event.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] You can pass a file with the policy to kube-apiserver using the --audit-policy-file flag.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] If the flag is omitted, no events are logged.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Note that the rules field must be provided in the audit policy file.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] A policy with no (0) rules is treated as illegal.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] One main challenge with logging Kubernetes is understanding what logs are generated and how to use them.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Let’s start by examining the overall picture of Kubernetes' logging architecture.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] The first layer of logs that can be collected from a Kubernetes cluster are those being generated by your containerized applications.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] The easiest method for logging containers is to write to the standard output (stdout) and standard error (stderr) streams.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] For persisting container logs, the common approach is to write logs to a log file and then use a sidecar container.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] As shown below in the pod configuration above, a sidecar container will run in the same pod along with the application container, mounting the same volume and processing the logs separately.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] When a container running on Kubernetes writes its logs to stdout or stderr streams, the container engine streams them to the logging driver set by the Kubernetes configuration.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] In most cases, these logs will end up in the /var/log/containers directory on your host.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Docker supports multiple logging drivers but unfortunately, driver configuration is not supported via the Kubernetes API.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Once a container is terminated or restarted, kubelet stores logs on the node.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] To prevent these files from consuming all of the host’s storage, the Kubernetes node implements a log rotation mechanism.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] When a container is evicted from the node, all containers with corresponding log files are evicted.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Depending on what operating system and additional services you’re running on your host machine, you might need to take a look at additional logs.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] In the Kubernetes cluster itself, there is a long list of cluster components that can be logged as well as additional data types that can be used (events, audit logs).
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Together, these different types of data can give you visibility into how Kubernetes is performing as a system.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Some of these components run in a container, and some of them run on the operating system level (in most cases, a systemd service).
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] The systemd services write to journald, and components running in containers write logs to the /var/log directory, unless the container engine has been configured to stream logs differently.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Kubernetes events can indicate any Kubernetes resource state changes and errors, such as exceeded resource quota or pending pods, as well as any informational messages.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Container supply chain security is critical for preventing attacks that exploit vulnerabilities in the software delivery process.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] A compromised supply chain can lead to malicious code being deployed into production environments, potentially affecting thousands of containers and applications.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Recent high-profile attacks (SolarWinds, Codecov, ua-parser-js) demonstrate the severe impact of supply chain compromises.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Implement image scanning: Regularly scan container images for vulnerabilities using tools like Clair, Trivy, or Aqua Security.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Secure CI/CD pipelines: Ensure that build processes are secure, with proper access controls and monitoring.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Sign and verify images: Use image signing tools like Notary or Cosign to ensure the integrity of container images.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Use private registries: Store container images in private registries with access controls to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Monitor for vulnerabilities: Continuously monitor for new vulnerabilities in dependencies and base images.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Implement runtime security: Use tools to monitor container behavior at runtime and detect anomalies.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] You must integrate security earlier into the container lifecycle and ensure alignment and shared goals between security and DevOps teams.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Security can (and should) be an enabler that allows your developers and DevOps teams to confidently build and deploy applications that are production-ready for scale, stability and security.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Leverage the native controls built into Kubernetes whenever available in order to enforce security policies so that your security controls don’t collide with the orchestrator.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Instead of using a third-party proxy or shim to enforce network segmentation, you could use Kubernetes network policies to ensure secure network communication.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] Note that manually triaging security incidents and policy violations is time consuming in sprawling Kubernetes environments.
[src:container-security/kubernetes-security-cheat-sheet-p02] For example, a deployment containing a vulnerability with severity score of 7 or greater should be moved up in remediation priority if that deployment contains privileged containers and is open to the Internet but moved down if it’s in a test environment and supporting a non-critical app.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:container-security/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:container-security/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:container-security/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:container-security/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:container-security/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:container-security/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:container-security/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:container-security/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Linux namespaces, alongside cgroups (control groups), are the foundational technologies underpinning modern OS-level virtualization and Linux containerization platforms such as Docker, Kubernetes, LXC, and Podman.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] While cgroups dictate *how much* of a system's resources a process can use (such as CPU, memory, and disk I/O limits), namespaces dictate *what* a process is allowed to see and interact with.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The term "namespace" is often used to denote a specific type of namespace (e.g., process ID namespace) as well as a particular space of names.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] A Linux system begins with a single initial namespace of each type, which is shared by all processes.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Processes can subsequently create additional namespaces or join existing ones, allowing complex, nested isolation boundaries.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Linux namespaces were heavily inspired by the wider namespace functionality utilized throughout the Plan 9 from Bell Labs operating system, which treated everything as a file and provided per-process namespace isolation.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The Linux namespace implementation originated in 2002 with the release of the 2.4.19 kernel.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The first namespace introduced was the mount namespace, pioneered by kernel developer Al Viro, which isolated filesystem mount points.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Because it was the first of its kind, the system call flag introduced for it was simply named `CLONE_NEWNS` (New Namespace), a name that does not specify "mount" and is often considered a historical artifact.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] As of Linux kernel version 5.6, there are exactly eight kinds of namespaces.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Namespace functionality operates uniformly across all kinds: each process is associated with a namespace and can only see or use the resources associated with that specific namespace, including its descendant namespaces where applicable.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] This provides each process (or group of processes) with a unique, compartmentalized view of the system.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Mount namespaces, the first namespace to be added to Linux, control mount points.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] They provide a process with an isolated view of the filesystem hierarchy.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Upon creation, the mounts from the current mount namespace are initially copied to the new namespace.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] However, mount points created or unmounted afterwards do not propagate between namespaces by default.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Using the Linux shared subtrees feature, it is possible to configure specific mount points to propagate events (such as a USB drive being mounted) between the host and the container, or vice versa.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The clone flag used to create a new namespace of this type is `CLONE_NEWNS`.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The PID namespace provides processes with an independent set of process IDs (PIDs).
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] When a new process is created within a new PID namespace, it will have a distinct PID for each namespace from its current namespace up to the initial (root) PID namespace.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Hence, processes in the initial PID namespace (like the host operating system) are able to see all processes across all containers, albeit with different PIDs than those seen inside the containers.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The first process created in a PID namespace is assigned process ID number 1.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] It receives much of the same special treatment as the host system's normal init process.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Most notably, any orphaned processes within the namespace are automatically reparented to this PID 1 process.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] If this PID 1 process terminates, the kernel will immediately terminate all other processes within that PID namespace and any of its descendants by sending them a `SIGKILL` signal.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Network namespaces virtualize the network stack.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Upon creation, a new network namespace contains only a loopback interface (`lo`), which is initially down.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Each network interface—whether physical or virtual—can only be present in exactly one network namespace at a time, but interfaces can be actively moved between namespaces by an administrator.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Each network namespace maintains a private set of IP addresses, its own routing table, socket listing, connection tracking table, firewall rules (such as iptables or nftables), and other network-related resources.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] To grant a container network connectivity, administrators typically create a Virtual Ethernet (`veth`) pair, placing one end in the host namespace and the other inside the container's network namespace, and then bridge the host end to a physical network.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Destroying a network namespace automatically destroys any virtual interfaces within it and moves any physical interfaces back to the initial network namespace.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] IPC namespaces isolate processes from SysV style inter-process communication mechanisms, as well as POSIX message queues.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] This prevents processes in different IPC namespaces from interacting with each other using common IPC identifiers.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] For example, two processes in different namespaces can use the same shared memory segment identifier to allocate memory via the SHM family of functions, and the kernel will guarantee that they are provided with two distinct, fully isolated regions of shared memory.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] UTS namespaces isolate two system identifiers: the hostname and the NIS domain name.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The name "UTS" originates from the data structure passed to the `uname` system call, which historically stands for UNIX Time-Sharing System.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] When a process creates a new UTS namespace, the hostname and domain name are copied from the caller's namespace.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The processes inside the new namespace can then change their hostname without affecting the host machine or other containers.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] User namespaces are a critical security feature designed to provide both privilege isolation and user identification segregation across multiple sets of processes.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Introduced completely in kernel 3.8, they are the backbone of unprivileged containers.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Like PID namespaces, user namespaces are nested, with each new namespace considered a child of the one that created it.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] A user namespace maintains a mapping table that converts user IDs (UIDs) and group IDs (GIDs) from the container's internal perspective to the host system's global perspective.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] This allows a process to possess root privileges (UID 0) inside the container, but mathematically map to an unprivileged, restricted user ID (e.g., UID 100000) on the underlying host machine.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] If a vulnerability allows the container's "root" process to break out of the namespace, the host system will still treat it as the restricted user ID, severely limiting the potential damage.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The cgroup namespace hides the identity of the control group hierarchy to which a process belongs.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Before this namespace existed, a process inside a container could inspect `/proc/self/cgroup` and see the entire path of its cgroup relative to the host system (e.g., `/sys/fs/cgroup/memory/docker/container_id`).
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] By virtualizing the cgroup filesystem view, a process inside a cgroup namespace will see its own cgroup directory as the root (`/`).
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] This prevents information leaks about the host's underlying infrastructure and allows container orchestration tools to seamlessly migrate containers between nodes without conflicting cgroup paths.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] This namespace type has existed since March 2016 in Linux 4.6.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The time namespace allows processes to observe different system times.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] It was introduced in Linux 5.6 in March 2020.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Specifically, it isolates two specific kernel clocks: `CLOCK_MONOTONIC` and `CLOCK_BOOTTIME`.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] When a container is migrated from one physical host to another or restored from a snapshot, the system uptime and monotonic clock values of the new host will naturally differ from the old one.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The time namespace allows the container runtime to set clock offsets, ensuring that applications inside the container do not experience sudden, disruptive jumps in time.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The syslog namespace was proposed by Rui Xiang, an engineer at Huawei, to isolate kernel logging rings.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] However, the proposal was not merged into the mainline Linux kernel.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Instead, user-space solutions largely fulfilled this requirement; for instance, systemd introduced the concept of "journal namespaces" in February 2020 to provide isolated log environments.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The Integrity Measurement Architecture (IMA) is a kernel security subsystem that measures files before they are accessed to ensure they have not been tampered with.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Standard IMA operates globally, which causes conflicts in containerized environments.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Ongoing development by the kernel community—with significant contributions from IBM and Huawei—aims to introduce an IMA namespace.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] This would allow each container to maintain isolated Platform Configuration Registers (PCR), unique Measurement Logs (ML), and independent appraisal keys, thereby bringing hardware-level cryptographic attestation directly to individual containers.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] To facilitate privilege isolation for administrative actions, every namespace type is tied to a user namespace.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] When a non-user namespace is created, it is considered "owned" by the user namespace that was active at the moment of its creation.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] A user with administrative privileges (specifically, possessing the `CAP_SYS_ADMIN` capability) in the owning user namespace is allowed to perform administrative actions on that namespace.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] For example, if a process has administrative permissions to change the IP address of a network interface, it may do so, but only if its active user namespace owns that specific network namespace.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Because the initial (host) user namespace is the ancestor of all other namespaces, the host's root user inherently retains administrative control over all namespace types across the entire system.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Namespaces are represented as virtual file objects within the kernel, accessible via the `procfs` pseudo-filesystem.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The kernel exposes the namespace associations of each running process at the path `/proc/*pid*/ns/*kind*`.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Like many non-file resources in `/proc`, these entries manifest as special symbolic links.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Reading the link yields a string formatted as `*kind*:[*inode_number*]`.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] These inode numbers correspond one-to-one with unique namespace objects in the kernel memory.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] If two processes show the same inode number for a specific namespace kind (e.g., `net:[4026531969]`), they share that namespace.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Additionally, for namespaces where children processes might inherit different traits than the parent itself (such as PID or user namespaces), the kernel provides `/proc/*pid*/ns/*kind*_for_children` links.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] If a namespace is no longer referenced by any part of the system, the kernel will automatically destroy it.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The cleanup process for the contained resources varies depending on the namespace kind.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Linux namespaces are ubiquitously adopted across the modern software landscape.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] They are universally combined with cgroups to build container technologies.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Examples include Docker, LXC (Linux Containers), Podman, and container orchestration systems like Kubernetes.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Beyond pure containers, namespaces are extensively utilized for process sandboxing and security.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Google Chrome and Chromium heavily rely on user, PID, and network namespaces to sandbox web rendering processes, severely limiting the damage an attacker can inflict if a renderer is compromised.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Package formats like Flatpak and Snap employ namespaces to isolate desktop applications from the host filesystem and user data.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Furthermore, the init system systemd uses namespaces to secure system services.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Directives such as `PrivateNetwork=yes` or `PrivateTmp=yes` in a systemd service file instruct the kernel to spawn the daemon inside isolated network and mount namespaces, respectively.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] Command-line utilities also make use of these features.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] The `util-linux` package includes the `unshare` command, which allows users to start shells or scripts inside newly created namespaces.
[src:container-security/linux-namespaces] This command spawns a process in new user, PID, and mount namespaces, effectively acting as a modern, far more secure equivalent to the traditional `chroot`.
